[00:00.38]	[France. KING LEWIS XI's palace.,]
[00:01.14]	[Flourish. Enter KING LEWIS XI, his sister BONA,
[00:01.52]	+ his Admiral, called BOURBON, PRINCE EDWARD, QUEEN
[00:01.91]	+ MARGARET, and OXFORD. KING LEWIS XI sits, and
[00:02.29]	+ riseth up again]
[00:02.67]KING LEWIS XI	Fair Queen of England, worthy Margaret,
[00:05.47]	Sit down with us: it ill befits thy state
[00:08.47]	And birth, that thou shouldst stand while Lewis doth sit.
[00:12.42]QUEEN MARGARET	No, mighty King of France: now Margaret
[00:15.22]	Must strike her sail and learn awhile to serve
[00:18.60]	Where kings command. I was, I must confess,
[00:21.59]	Great Albion's queen in former golden days:
[00:24.72]	But now mischance hath trod my title down,
[00:27.78]	And with dishonour laid me on the ground;
[00:30.77]	Where I must take like seat unto my fortune,
[00:33.96]	And to my humble seat conform myself.
[00:36.70]KING LEWIS XI	Why, say, fair queen, whence springs this deep despair?
[00:40.39]QUEEN MARGARET	From such a cause as fills mine eyes with tears
[00:43.83]	And stops my tongue, while heart is drown'd in cares.
[00:47.53]KING LEWIS XI	Whate'er it be, be thou still like thyself,
[00:50.59]	And sit thee by our side:
[00:52.56]	[Seats her by him]
[00:53.33]	Yield not thy neck
[00:54.92]	To fortune's yoke, but let thy dauntless mind
[00:58.17]	Still ride in triumph over all mischance.
[01:01.16]	Be plain, Queen Margaret, and tell thy grief;
[01:04.28]	It shall be eased, if France can yield relief.
[01:07.53]QUEEN MARGARET	Those gracious words revive my drooping thoughts
[01:11.04]	And give my tongue-tied sorrows leave to speak.
[01:14.42]	Now, therefore, be it known to noble Lewis,
[01:17.41]	That Henry, sole possessor of my love,
[01:20.15]	Is of a king become a banish'd man,
[01:22.76]	And forced to live in Scotland a forlorn;
[01:25.76]	While proud ambitious Edward Duke of York
[01:28.82]	Usurps the regal title and the seat
[01:31.49]	Of England's true-anointed lawful king.
[01:34.36]	This is the cause that I, poor Margaret,
[01:37.23]	With this my son, Prince Edward, Henry's heir,
[01:40.41]	Am come to crave thy just and lawful aid;
[01:43.41]	And if thou fail us, all our hope is done:
[01:46.40]	Scotland hath will to help, but cannot help;
[01:49.52]	Our people and our peers are both misled,
[01:52.52]	Our treasures seized, our soldiers put to flight,
[01:55.96]	And, as thou seest, ourselves in heavy plight.
[01:59.14]KING LEWIS XI	Renowned queen, with patience calm the storm,
[02:02.33]	While we bethink a means to break it off.
[02:05.32]QUEEN MARGARET	The more we stay, the stronger grows our foe.
[02:08.51]KING LEWIS XI	The more I stay, the more I'll succor thee.
[02:11.57]QUEEN MARGARET	O, but impatience waiteth on true sorrow.
[02:14.50]	And see where comes the breeder of my sorrow!
[02:17.75]	[Enter WARWICK]
[02:18.51]KING LEWIS XI	What's he approacheth boldly to our presence?
[02:21.76]QUEEN MARGARET	Our Earl of Warwick, Edward's greatest friend.
[02:25.01]KING LEWIS XI	Welcome, brave Warwick! What brings thee to France?
[02:28.52]	[He descends. She ariseth]
[02:29.28]QUEEN MARGARET	Ay, now begins a second storm to rise;
[02:32.02]	For this is he that moves both wind and tide.
[02:35.27]WARWICK	From worthy Edward, King of Albion,
[02:37.82]	My lord and sovereign, and thy vowed friend,
[02:40.94]	I come, in kindness and unfeigned love,
[02:43.75]	First, to do greetings to thy royal person;
[02:46.80]	And then to crave a league of amity;
[02:49.48]	And lastly, to confirm that amity
[02:51.96]	With a nuptial knot, if thou vouchsafe to grant
[02:55.34]	That virtuous Lady Bona, thy fair sister,
[02:58.27]	To England's king in lawful marriage.
[03:01.01]QUEEN MARGARET	[Aside] If that go forward, Henry's hope is done.
[03:04.33]WARWICK	[To BONA] And, gracious madam, in our king's behalf,
[03:07.64]	I am commanded, with your leave and favour,
[03:10.70]	Humbly to kiss your hand, and with my tongue
[03:13.88]	To tell the passion of my sovereign's heart;
[03:17.07]	Where fame, late entering at his heedful ears,
[03:20.32]	Hath placed thy beauty's image and thy virtue.
[03:23.63]QUEEN MARGARET	King Lewis and Lady Bona, hear me speak,
[03:26.50]	Before you answer Warwick. His demand
[03:29.24]	Springs not from Edward's well-meant honest love,
[03:32.74]	But from deceit bred by necessity;
[03:35.29]	For how can tyrants safely govern home,
[03:38.16]	Unless abroad they purchase great alliance?
[03:41.28]	To prove him tyrant this reason may suffice,
[03:44.47]	That Henry liveth still: but were he dead,
[03:47.46]	Yet here Prince Edward stands, King Henry's son.
[03:50.84]	Look, therefore, Lewis, that by this league and marriage
[03:54.66]	Thou draw not on thy danger and dishonour;
[03:57.72]	For though usurpers sway the rule awhile,
[04:00.71]	Yet heavens are just, and time suppresseth wrongs.
[04:04.22]WARWICK	Injurious Margaret!
[04:05.81]PRINCE EDWARD	And why not queen?
[04:07.34]WARWICK	Because thy father Henry did usurp;
[04:09.95]	And thou no more are prince than she is queen.
[04:13.27]OXFORD	Then Warwick disannuls great John of Gaunt,
[04:16.39]	Which did subdue the greatest part of Spain;
[04:19.57]	And, after John of Gaunt, Henry the Fourth,
[04:22.57]	Whose wisdom was a mirror to the wisest;
[04:25.50]	And, after that wise prince, Henry the Fifth,
[04:28.62]	Who by his prowess conquered all France:
[04:31.55]	From these our Henry lineally descends.
[04:34.42]WARWICK	Oxford, how haps it, in this smooth discourse,
[04:37.61]	You told not how Henry the Sixth hath lost
[04:40.73]	All that which Henry Fifth had gotten?
[04:43.53]	Methinks these peers of France should smile at that.
[04:47.23]	But for the rest, you tell a pedigree
[04:49.97]	Of threescore and two years; a silly time
[04:52.96]	To make prescription for a kingdom's worth.
[04:56.08]OXFORD	Why, Warwick, canst thou speak against thy liege,
[04:59.46]	Whom thou obeyed'st thirty and six years,
[05:02.45]	And not bewray thy treason with a blush?
[05:05.39]WARWICK	Can Oxford, that did ever fence the right,
[05:08.38]	Now buckler falsehood with a pedigree?
[05:11.18]	For shame! leave Henry, and call Edward king.
[05:14.31]OXFORD	Call him my king by whose injurious doom
[05:17.30]	My elder brother, the Lord Aubrey Vere,
[05:20.10]	Was done to death? and more than so, my father,
[05:23.35]	Even in the downfall of his mellow'd years,
[05:26.48]	When nature brought him to the door of death?
[05:29.73]	No, Warwick, no; while life upholds this arm,
[05:32.78]	This arm upholds the house of Lancaster.
[05:35.71]WARWICK	And I the house of York.
[05:37.63]KING LEWIS XI	Queen Margaret, Prince Edward, and Oxford,
[05:40.56]	Vouchsafe, at our request, to stand aside,
[05:43.49]	While I use further conference with Warwick.
[05:46.67]	[They stand aloof]
[05:47.44]QUEEN MARGARET	Heavens grant that Warwick's words bewitch him not!
[05:51.07]KING LEWIS XI	Now Warwick, tell me, even upon thy conscience,
[05:54.32]	Is Edward your true king? for I were loath
[05:57.38]	To link with him that were not lawful chosen.
[06:00.63]WARWICK	Thereon I pawn my credit and mine honour.
[06:03.62]KING LEWIS XI	But is he gracious in the people's eye?
[06:06.49]WARWICK	The more that Henry was unfortunate.
[06:09.17]KING LEWIS XI	Then further, all dissembling set aside,
[06:12.03]	Tell me for truth the measure of his love
[06:15.09]	Unto our sister Bona.
[06:16.81]WARWICK	Such it seems
[06:18.09]	As may beseem a monarch like himself.
[06:20.83]	Myself have often heard him say and swear
[06:23.88]	That this his love was an eternal plant,
[06:26.81]	Whereof the root was fix'd in virtue's ground,
[06:30.13]	The leaves and fruit maintain'd with beauty's sun,
[06:33.70]	Exempt from envy, but not from disdain,
[06:36.50]	Unless the Lady Bona quit his pain.
[06:39.11]KING LEWIS XI	Now, sister, let us hear your firm resolve.
[06:42.11]BONA	Your grant, or your denial, shall be mine:
[06:45.04]	[To WARWICK]
[06:45.80]	Yet I confess that often ere this day,
[06:48.61]	When I have heard your king's desert recounted,
[06:51.98]	Mine ear hath tempted judgment to desire.
[06:54.98]KING LEWIS XI	Then, Warwick, thus: our sister shall be Edward's;
[06:58.35]	And now forthwith shall articles be drawn
[07:01.41]	Touching the jointure that your king must make,
[07:04.79]	Which with her dowry shall be counterpoised.
[07:07.98]	Draw near, Queen Margaret, and be a witness
[07:11.03]	That Bona shall be wife to the English king.
[07:14.22]PRINCE EDWARD	To Edward, but not to the English king.
[07:17.02]QUEEN MARGARET	Deceitful Warwick! it was thy device
[07:19.70]	By this alliance to make void my suit:
[07:22.50]	Before thy coming Lewis was Henry's friend.
[07:25.62]KING LEWIS XI	And still is friend to him and Margaret:
[07:28.56]	But if your title to the crown be weak,
[07:31.42]	As may appear by Edward's good success,
[07:34.29]	Then 'tis but reason that I be released
[07:37.16]	From giving aid which late I promised.
[07:39.96]	Yet shall you have all kindness at my hand
[07:43.08]	That your estate requires and mine can yield.
[07:46.33]WARWICK	Henry now lives in Scotland at his ease,
[07:49.26]	Where having nothing, nothing can he lose.
[07:52.26]	And as for you yourself, our quondam queen,
[07:55.32]	You have a father able to maintain you;
[07:58.18]	And better 'twere you troubled him than France.
[08:01.50]QUEEN MARGARET	Peace, impudent and shameless Warwick, peace,
[08:04.62]	Proud setter up and puller down of kings!
[08:07.61]	I will not hence, till, with my talk and tears,
[08:10.86]	Both full of truth, I make King Lewis behold
[08:14.05]	Thy sly conveyance and thy lord's false love;
[08:17.30]	For both of you are birds of selfsame feather.
[08:20.61]	[Post blows a horn within]
